{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure boundary is the CLI-to-git subprocess contract: rename detection depends on actual git diff/name-status behavior and flags, not just local parsing logic. A mock git output can hide bugs where the CLI invokes git in a way that never emits rename records. Higher levels are disqualified by the behavior text (no AI/LLM or multi-agent pipeline).","test_description":"Create a real temp git repo, commit a file, rename it, run the CLI as a subprocess against that repo, and assert report shows 1 rename and 0 added/0 deleted for that change.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.65,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure often appears only with real git/subprocess/encoding behavior for binary diffs; in-process fakes usually return sanitized text and miss crash paths. This behavior explicitly depends on binary handling in real repo diffs. Higher levels are disqualified by the behavior text (no AI/LLM step).","test_description":"In a real temp git repo, add or modify a binary file, run the CLI subprocess, assert exit code is success, and verify binary file changes are reflected in counts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This boundary depends on real git behavior for unborn HEAD/no-commit repositories (often specific exit codes/messages). Moc